SIMPLE: infectious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infectious
<hw>In*fec"tious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>infectieux</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Having qualities that may infect; communicable or
caused by infection; pestilential; epidemic; <as>as, an
<ex>infectious</ex> fever; <ex>infectious</ex> clothing;
<ex>infectious</ex> water; <ex>infectious</ex> vices.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where the <qex>infectious</qex> pestilence.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Corrupting, or tending to corrupt or contaminate;
vitiating; demoralizing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It [the court] is necessary for the polishing of manners . . . but
it is <qex>infectious</qex> even to the best morals to live always in
it.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Contaminating with illegality;
exposing to seizure and forfeiture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Contraband articles are said to be of an <qex>infectious</qex>
nature.</q> <rj><qau>Kent.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Capable of being easily diffused or spread;
sympathetic; readily communicated; <as>as, <ex>infectious</ex>
mirth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The laughter was so genuine as to be <qex>infectious</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Black.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Contagious</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infectious disease</ent>⟦br⟧
